note2 = Note.create(user_id: 1, notebook_id: 1, title: "Dynamic Array", body: "<p>Static arrays are arrays that have a fixed amount of memory allocated to them.</p><pre><code>def initialize(capacity = 8)\n   @store = StaticArray.new(capacity)\n   @start_idx,@ count = 0, 0\n   @length = capacity\nend</code></pre><p>Syntactical Sugar for array access:</p><pre><code>def [](i)\n   @store[idx(i)]\nend</code></pre><p>Circular buffer implementing \"logical indicies\".</p><pre><code>def idx(i)\n   (@start_idx + i) % @length\nend</code></pre><p>O(1) amortized time complexity. All we are doing is moving @start_idx back by one (O(1)) and doing some variable assignment and arithmetic.</p><p></p><p>Resizing is expensive in terms of time complexity, but we can predict fairly well when it will occur (push / unshift n times, where n = capacity).\n\nIn Ruby, mod of a negative number gives a positive number. Make sure this is the case before implementing in different languages.</p><pre><code>def unshift(val)\n   resize! if @count == @length\n   i = (@start_idx - 1) % @length\n   @store[i] = val\n   @count += 1\n   @start_idx = i\nend</code></pre><p>@length = @length * 2, use this as the new capacity.\n\nCopy over everything to the new store. O(n), but this does not happen often so the overall amortized complexity is O(1). Note that new_store[i] uses StaticArray's array access, while self[i] uses #[], which we defined on line 7.</p><p></p><p>Old @store is garbage collected</p><p></p><pre><code>def resize\n   new_store = StaticArray.new(@length *= 2)\n   @length.times { |i| new_store[i] = self[i] }\n   @start_idx = 0\n   @store = new_store\nend </code></pre><p></p>")

note3 = Note.create(user_id: 1, notebook_id: 1, title: "Merge Sort", body: "<ul><li><p>Worst Case Performance: O(n log n)</p></li></ul><ul><li><p>Best Case Performance: O(n log n)</p></li><li><p>Average Case Performance O(n log n)</p></li></ul><p></p><p>Pseudocode:</p><pre><code>function merge_sort(list m)\n    // Base case. A list of zero or one elements is sorted, by definition.\n    if length of m ≤ 1 then\n        return m\n\n    // Recursive case. First, divide the list into equal-sized sublists\n    // consisting of the even and odd-indexed elements.\n    var left := empty list\n    var right := empty list\n    for each x with index i in m do\n        if i is odd then\n            add x to left\n        else\n            add x to right\n\n    // Recursively sort both sublists.\n    left := merge_sort(left)\n    right := merge_sort(right)\n\n    // Then merge the now-sorted sublists.\n    return merge(left, right)</code></pre>")

note4 = Note.create(user_id: 1, notebook_id: 1, title: "Quick Sort", body: "<ul><li><p>Worst Case Performance: O(n^2)</p></li></ul><ul><li><p>Best Case Performance: O(n log n)</p></li><li><p>Average Case Performance O(n log n)</p></li></ul><p></p><p>Pseudocode:</p><pre><code>algorithm quicksort(A, lo, hi) is\n    if lo &lt; hi then\n        p := partition(A, lo, hi)\n        quicksort(A, lo, p – 1)\n        quicksort(A, p + 1, hi)\n</code></pre><pre><code>algorithm partition(A, lo, hi) is\n    pivot := A[hi]\n    i := lo        // place for swapping\n    for j := lo to hi – 1 do\n        if A[j] ≤ pivot then\n            swap A[i] with A[j]\n            i := i + 1\n    swap A[i] with A[hi]\n    return i</code></pre>")

note5 = Note.create(user_id: 1, notebook_id: 1, title: "Bubble Sort", body: "<ul><li><p>Worst Case Performance: O(n)^2</p></li><li><p>Best Case Performance: O(n)</p></li><li><p>Average Case Performance O(n)^2</p></li></ul><pre><code>def bubble_sort(list)\n  return list if list.size &lt;= 1 # already sorted\n  swapped = true\n  while swapped do\n    swapped = false\n    0.upto(list.size-2) do |i|\n      if list[i] &gt; list[i+1]\n        list[i], list[i+1] = list[i+1], list[i] # swap values\n        swapped = true\n      end\n    end    \n  end\n\n  list\nend</code></pre>")



